  940.  /**
    941. 

  941.   * Plucks values from an array. Effectevily the same as using a array.map implementation. However the porperty specified supports
    942. 

  942.   * a "dot" notation to access nested properties.
    943. 

  943.   *
    944.

  945.   *
    946. 

  946.   *   var arr = [

  77. 1function buildDateEXP(pattern, tokens) {
    78. 

  78. 55    return pattern.replace(/([a-z])\1*/ig,function (match) {
    79. 

  79.          // Build a simple regexp.  Avoid captures, which would ruin the tokens list
    80. 

  80. 197        var s,
    81. 

  81.              c = match.charAt(0),
    82. 

  82.              l = match.length,
    83. 

  83.              p2 = '', p3 = '';
    84. 

  84. 197        p2 = '0?';
    85. 

  85. 197        p3 = '0{0,2}';
    86. 

  86. 197        if (c === 'y') {
    87. 

  87. 33            s = '\\d{2,4}';
    88. 

  88. 164        } else if (c === "M") {
    89. 

  89. 33            s = (l > 2) ? '\\S+?' : '1[0-2]|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    90. 

  90. 131        } else if (c === "D") {
    91. 

  91. 4            s = '[12][0-9][0-9]|3[0-5][0-9]|36[0-6]|' + p3 + '[1-9][0-9]|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    92. 

  92. 127        } else if (c === "d") {
    93. 

  93. 31            s = '3[01]|[12]\\d|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    94. 

  94. 96        } else if (c === "w") {
    95. 

  95. 4            s = '[1-4][0-9]|5[0-3]|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    96. 

  96. 92        } else if (c === "E") {
    97. 

  97. 12            s = '\\S+';
    98. 

  98. 80        } else if (c === "h") {
    99. 

  99. 10            s = '1[0-2]|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    100. 

  100. 70        } else if (c === "K") {
    101. 

  101. 4            s = '1[01]|' + p2 + '\\d';
    102. 

  102. 66        } else if (c === "H") {
    103. 

  103. 2            s = '1\\d|2[0-3]|' + p2 + '\\d';
    104. 

  104. 64        } else if (c === "k") {
    105. 

  105. 2            s = '1\\d|2[0-4]|' + p2 + '[1-9]';
    106. 

  106. 62        } else if (c === "m" || c === "s") {
    107. 

  107. 30            s = '[0-5]\\d';
    108. 

  108. 32        } else if (c === "S") {
    109. 

  109. 10            s = '\\d{' + l + '}';
    110. 

  110. 22        } else if (c === "a") {
    111. 

  111. 6            var am = 'AM', pm = 'PM';
    112. 

  112. 6            s = am + '|' + pm;
    113. 

  113. 6            if (am !== am.toLowerCase()) {
    114. 

  114. 6                s += '|' + am.toLowerCase();
    115. 

  115.              }
    116. 

  116. 6            if (pm !== pm.toLowerCase()) {
    117. 

  117. 6                s += '|' + pm.toLowerCase();
    118. 

  118.              }
    119. 

  119. 6            s = s.replace(/\./g, "\\.");
    120. 

  120. 16        } else if (c === 'v' || c === 'z' || c === 'Z' || c === 'G' || c === 'q' || c === 'Q') {
    121. 

  121. 12            s = ".*";
    122. 

  122.          } else {
    123. 

  123. 4            s = c === " " ? "\\s*" : c + "*";
    124. 

  124.          }
    125. 

  125. 197        if (tokens) {
    126. 

  126. 197            tokens.push(match);
    127. 

  127.          }
    128. 

  128.  
    129. 

  129. 197        return "(" + s + ")"; // add capture
    130. 

  130.      }).replace(/[\xa0 ]/g, "[\\s\\xa0]"); // normalize whitespace.  Need explicit handling of \xa0 for IE.
    131. 

  131.  }

  423.      /**
    424. 

  424.       * Parses a date string into a date object

  426.       * @example
    427.

    432.

    436.

    437. 

  437.       * <ul>
    438. 

  438.       *                  <li> G    Era designator    Text    AD</li>
    439. 

  439.       *                  <li> y    Year    Year    1996; 96</li>
    440. 

  440.       *                  <li> M    Month in year    Month    July; Jul; 07</li>
    441. 

  441.       *                  <li> w    Week in year    Number    27</li>

    449. 

  449.       *                  <li> K    Hour in am/pm (0-11)    Number    0</li>
    450. 

  450.       *                  <li> h    Hour in am/pm (1-12)    Number    12</li>
    451. 

  451.       *                  <li> m    Minute in hour    Number    30</li>
    452. 

  452.       *                  <li> s    Second in minute    Number    55</li>
    453. 

  453.       *                  <li> S    Millisecond    Number    978</li>
    454. 

  454.       *                  <li> z    Time zone    General time zone    Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08:00</li>
    455. 

  455.       *                  <li> Z    Time zone    RFC 822 time zone    -0800 </li>
    456. 

  456.       * </ul>

    458.

  546. 14                        result[4] = v;

    549. 

  549. 26                    } else if (type === "S") {

    571. 

  571. 2                return null;
    572.

    574.

  579.      /**
    580. 

  580.       * Formats a date to the specidifed format string
    581. 

  581.       *
    582. 

  582.       * @example
    583. 

  583.       *
    584. 

  584.       * var date = new Date(2006, 7, 11, 0, 55, 12, 345);
    585.

    586. 

  586.       * comb.date.format(date, "M/dd/yy"); //"8/11/06"
    587. 

  587.       * comb.date.format(date, "E"); //"6"
    588. 

  588.       * comb.date.format(date, "h:m a"); //"12:55 AM"
    589. 

  589.       * comb.date.format(date, 'h:m:s'); //"12:55:12"
    590. 

  590.       * comb.date.format(date, 'h:m:s.SS'); //"12:55:12.35"
    591. 

  591.       * comb.date.format(date, 'k:m:s.SS'); //"24:55:12.35"
    592. 

  592.       * comb.date.format(date, 'H:m:s.SS'); //"0:55:12.35"
    593. 

  593.       * comb.date.format(date, "ddMMyyyy"); //"11082006"
    594. 

  594.       *
    595. 

  595.       * @param date the date to format
    596. 

  596.       * @param {String} format the format of the date composed of the following options
    597. 

  597.       * <ul>
    598. 

  598.       *                  <li> G    Era designator    Text    AD</li>
    599. 

  599.       *                  <li> y    Year    Year    1996; 96</li>
    600. 

  600.       *                  <li> M    Month in year    Month    July; Jul; 07</li>
    601. 

  601.       *                  <li> w    Week in year    Number    27</li>
    602. 

  602.       *                  <li> W    Week in month    Number    2</li>
    603. 

  603.       *                  <li> D    Day in year    Number    189</li>
    604. 

  604.       *                  <li> d    Day in month    Number    10</li>
    605. 

  605.       *                  <li> E    Day in week    Text    Tuesday; Tue</li>
    606. 

  606.       *                  <li> a    Am/pm marker    Text    PM</li>
    607. 

  607.       *                  <li> H    Hour in day (0-23)    Number    0</li>
    608. 

  608.       *                  <li> k    Hour in day (1-24)    Number    24</li>
    609. 

  609.       *                  <li> K    Hour in am/pm (0-11)    Number    0</li>
    610. 

  610.       *                  <li> h    Hour in am/pm (1-12)    Number    12</li>
    611. 

  611.       *                  <li> m    Minute in hour    Number    30</li>
    612. 

  612.       *                  <li> s    Second in minute    Number    55</li>
    613. 

  613.       *                  <li> S    Millisecond    Number    978</li>
    614. 

  614.       *                  <li> z    Time zone    General time zone    Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08:00</li>
    615. 

  615.       *                  <li> Z    Time zone    RFC 822 time zone    -0800 </li>
    616. 

  616.       * </ul>
    617. 

  617.       */
    618. 

  618.      format:function (date, format, utc) {
    619. 

  619. 79        utc = utc || false;
    620. 

  620. 79        var fullYear, month, day, d, hour, minute, second, millisecond;
    621. 

  621. 79        if (utc) {

  640. 79        return format.replace(/([a-z])\1*/ig, function (match, options) {
    641. 

  641. 381            var s, pad, h,
    642. 

  642.                  c = match.charAt(0),
    643. 

  643.                  l = match.length;

  644. 381            if (c === 'd') {

  647. 338            } else if (c === "H" && !s) {

  650. 307            } else if (c === 'm' && !s) {

  651. 41                s = "" + minute;

  652. 41                pad = true;

  653. 266            } else if (c === 's') {

    672.

  151.  /**
    152. 

  152.   * @ignoreCode
    153. 

  153.   * @class <p>An AVL tree is a self-balancing binary search tree.
    154. 

  154.   *    In an AVL tree, the heights of the two child subtrees of any node differ by at most one.
    155. 

  155.   *    Lookup, insertion, and deletion all take O(log n) time in both the average and worst cases,
    156. 

  156.   *    where n is the number of nodes in the tree prior to the operation.
    157. 

  157.   *    Insertions and deletions may require the tree to be rebalanced by one or more tree rotations.</p>
    158. 

  158.   * <p>AVL trees are more rigidly balanced than red-black trees, leading to slower insertion and removal but faster retrieval</p>
    159. 

  159.   *
    160. 

  160.   * <b>Performance</b>
    161. 

  161.   * <table>

  309.  /**
    310. 

  310.   * Defines a new class to be used
    311. 

  311.   *
    312. 

  312.   * <p>
    313. 

  313.   *     Class methods
    314. 

  314.   *     <ul>
    315. 

  315.   *         <li>as(module | object, name): exports the object to module or the object with the name</li>
    316. 

  316.   *         <li>mixin(mixin) : mixes in an object</li>
    317. 

  317.   *     </ul>
    318. 

  318.   *     </br>
    319. 

  319.   *     Instance methods
    320. 

  320.   *     <ul>
    321. 

  321.   *         <li>_super(argumnents, [?newargs]): calls the super of the current method</li>
    322. 

  322.   *     </ul>
    323. 

  323.   *
    324. 

  324.   *      </br>
    325. 

  325.   *     Instance properties
    326. 

  326.   *     <ul>
    327. 

  327.   *         <li>_static: use to reference class properties and methods</li>
    328. 

  328.   *     </ul>
    329. 

  329.   *
    330. 

  330.   * </p>
    331. 

  331.   *
    332. 

  332.   *
    333. 

  333.   * @example
    334. 

  334.   *  //Class without a super class
    335. 

  335.   * var Mammal = comb.define(null, {
    336. 

  336.   *      instance : {
    337. 

  337.   *

  339.   *              options = options || {};
    340. 

  340.   *              this._super(arguments);
    341. 

  341.   *              this._type = options.type || "mammal";

  342.   *          },
    343. 

  343.   *
    344. 

  344.   *          speak : function() {
    345. 

  345.   *              return  "A mammal of type " + this._type + " sounds like";
    346. 

  346.   *          },
    347. 

  347.   *
    348. 

  348.   *          //Define your getters
    349. 

  349.   *          getters : {
    350. 

  350.   *              type : function() {
    351. 

  351.   *                  return this._type;
    352. 

  352.   *              }
    353. 

  353.   *          },
    354. 

  354.   *
    355. 

  355.   *           //Define your setters
    356. 

  356.   *          setters : {
    357. 

  357.   *              type : function(t) {
    358. 

  358.   *                  this._type = t;
    359. 

  359.   *              }
    360. 

  360.   *          }
    361. 

  361.   *      },
    362. 

  362.   *
    363. 

  363.   *      //Define your static methods
    364. 

  364.   *      static : {
    365. 

  365.   *          soundOff : function() {
    366. 

  366.   *              return "Im a mammal!!";
    367. 

  367.   *          }

  22.   *

  23.   * ##Overview

  26.   *
    27. 

  27.   * * [OO utilties](./define.html)
    28. 

  28.   * * Collections
    29. 

  29.   * * [Logging](./logging.html)

    35. 

  35.   *
    36. 

  36.   * `npm install comb`
    37. 

  37.   *
    38. 

  38.   * ###[Getting Started](./introduction.html)
    39. 

  39.   *
    40. 

  40.   * ##Highlights
    41. 

  41.   *
    42. 

  42.   * * 100% test coverage!
    43. 

  43.   * * comb([define](./comb.html#.define)|[singleton](./comb.html#.singleton))
    44. 

  44.   *   * The backbone of comb.
    45. 

  45.   *   * Options for classical inheritance models as well as mixins(pseudo multi-inheritance)
    46. 

  46.   *   * You can call this._super from any method. Including statically defined ones!
    47. 

  47.   *   * Access to your class level properties within an instance
    48. 

  48.   * * Logging
    49. 

  49.   *   * Logger inheritance through name spaces
    50. 

  50.   *   * Predefined [level](./comb_logging_Level.html) level definition along with the ability to define your own.
    51. 

  51.   *   * Multiple appenders including
    52. 

  52.   *      * [FileAppender](./comb_logging_appenders_FileAppender.html) - log it to a file
    53. 

  53.   *      * [RollingFileAppender](./comb_logging_appenders_RollingFileAppender.html) - log it to a file up to a customizable size then create a new one.
    54. 

  54.   *      * [JSONAppender](./comb_logging_appenders_JSONAppender.html) - write it out as JSON to a file.
    55. 

  55.   *      * [ConsoleAppender](./comb_logging_appenders_ConsoleAppender.html)- log it to the console
    56. 

  56.   *   * Configurable with [files OR programatically](./comb_logger.html#.configure)
    57. 

  57.   * * Collections
    58. 

  58.   *   * [RedBlackTree](./comb_collections_RedBlackTree.html)
    59. 

  59.   *   * [AVLTree](./comb_collections_AVLTree.html)
    60. 

  60.   *   * [AnderssonTree](./comb_collections_AnderssonTree.html)

  157. 1var logging = comb.logging;
    158. 

  158.  
    159. 

  159.  /**
    160. 

  160.   * @class This class is the entry point for all logging actions in comb.
    161. 

  161.   * <p><b>Logger should be retrieved by calling Logger.getLogger() NOT through the new keyword</b><p>
    162. 

  162.   * <p>
    163. 

  163.   *     All loggers in comb follow a heirarchy of inheritance based on a dot notation.
    164. 

  164.   *     <pre class="code">
    165. 

  165.   *                          rootLogger - ""
    166. 

  166.   *                                  /         \
    167. 

  167.   *                               "my"      "myOther"
    168. 

  168.   *                               /               \
    169. 

  169.   *                         "my.logger"       "myOther.logger"
    170. 

  170.   *                            /                     \
    171. 

  171.   *                       "my.logger.Log"        "myOther.logger.Log"
    172. 

  172.   *
    173. 

  173.   *     </pre>
    174. 

  174.   *     In the above Tree the rootLogger is the base for all logger. my and myOther inherit from rootLogger
    175. 

  175.   *     my.logger inherits from my, and myOther.logger inherits from myOther. The logs do not have to be retrieved in
    176. 

  176.   *     order. If I set rootLogger to ERROR level and added a console appender to it the appender and level will be
    177. 

  177.   *     added to all logs. However if I set my to INFO level and add a fileAppender to it the level and appender will
    178. 

  178.   *     only be added to logs in "my" subtree. If you set my.logger to not be additive then levels, and appenders will not
    179. 

  179.   *     propogate down to the rest of the tree.
    180. 

  180.   *
    181. 

  181.   * </p>
    182. 

  182.   *
    183. 

  183.   * <p>For information on levels see {@link comb.logging.Level}.</p>
    184. 

  184.   * <p>For information on appenders see
    185. 

  185.   *          <ul>
    186. 

  186.   *              <li>{@link comb.logging.appenders.Appender}</li>
    187. 

  187.   *              <li>{@link comb.logging.appenders.ConsoleAppender}</li>
    188. 

  188.   *              <li>{@link comb.logging.appenders.FileAppender}</li>
    189. 

  189.   *              <li>{@link comb.logging.appenders.JSONAppender}</li>
    190. 

  190.   *              <li>{@link comb.logging.appenders.RollingFileAppender}</li>
    191. 

  191.   *          </ul>
    192.

    633. 

  633. 9        eb = null;

  639. 1480        if (isPromiseLike(args)) {

    642. 

  642. 91            p = new PromiseList(args, true);

  644. 619            p = new Promise().callback(args);
    645.

    649.

  735.  /**

    737. 

  737.   * This is different than {@link comb.serial} in that it propogates results from one promise to the next, where
    738.

    758.

    759. 

  759.   * ]).then(function(results){
    760. 

  760.   *      console.log(results); //15
    761. 

  761.   * });
    762.

    765.

    766. 

  766.   * @memberOf comb
    767. 

  767.   */

  768. 1function chain(list) {

    770. 

  770. 4        return callNext(list, [], true);
    771. 

  771.      } else {
    772. 

  772. 1        throw new Error("When calling comb.serial the first argument must be an array");
    773. 

  773.      }
    774.

  777.  /**
    778. 

  778.   * Ensures that a promise is resolved before a the function can be run.
    779. 

  779.   *
    780. 

  780.   * For example suppose you have to ensure that you are connected to a database before you execute a function.
    781. 

  781.   *
    782. 

  782.   * ```
    783. 

  783.   * var findUser = comb.wait(connect(), function findUser(id){
    784. 

  784.   *      //this wont execute until we are connected
    785. 

  785.   *      return User.findById(id);
    786. 

  786.   * });
    787. 

  787.   *
    788. 

  788.   *  comb.when(findUser(1), findUser(2)).then(function(users){
    789. 

  789.   *      var user1 = users[0], user2 = users[1];
    790. 

  790.   *  });
    791. 

  791.   *
    792. 

  792.   * ```
    793. 

  793.   *
    794. 

  794.   * @param args variable number of arguments to wait on. See {@link comb.when}.
    795. 

  795.   * @param {Function} fn function that will wait.
    796. 

  796.   * @return {Function} a function that will wait on the args to resolve.
    797. 

  797.   * @memberOf comb
    798. 

  798.   * @static
    799. 

  799.   */
    800. 

  800. 1function wait(args, fn) {
